name: Shoo Fly, Don't Bother Me
comments: In it's current form known mostly as a "Children's song" and sung by children. Bishop wrote this song while assigned to command a company of black soldiers. One of the soldiers, dismissing some remarks of his fellow soldiers, exclaimed "Shoo fly, don't bother me," which inspired Bishop to write the song.  Bishop did publish a sheet music version of the song in 1869.  Other sources have credited Billy Reeves (lyrics) and Frank Campbell, or Rollin Howard, with the song. The first group to popularize the song was Bryant's Minstrels in 1869-70. The original lyrics are now considered offensive and only the chorus is typically sung now: Shoo, fly, don't bother me, Shoo, fly, don't bother me, Shoo, fly, don't bother me, For I belong to somebody.

name: Skip to My Lou
comments: aka "Skip to the Lou", "Fly in the Buttermilk", "Shoo Fly Shoo".  Dates back to the early 1800's.  Lyrics can very but often start out either - "Fly in the buttermilk, Shoo fly shoo, Skip to my lou, my darling!..." or can start out "Skip, skip, skip to my lou...." "Skip to My (The) Lou" is a popular American partner-stealing square dance from the 1840s. It begins with any number of couples skipping hand in hand around in a ring. A lone boy in the center of the moving circle of couples sings, "Lost my partner, what'll I do?" as the girls whirl past him. The young man in the center hesitates while he decides which girl to choose, singing, “I'll get another one just like you.” When he grasps the hand of his chosen one, the latter's partner moves to the center of the ring the game. The "lou" in the title comes from the word "loo", a Scottish word for "love". It is known today for being sung by Judy Garland in the 1944 film Meet Me in St. Louis . Completely unrelated to a modern song also called Skip to My Lou

name: Old King Cole
comments: Traditional British nursery rhyme dating back to 1708.  The poem describes a merry king who called for his pipe, bowl, and musicians, with the details varying among versions. The "bowl" is a drinking vessel, while the "pipe" is a musical instrument. Typical lyrics go - Old King Cole was a merry old soul, And a merry old soul was he; He called for his pipe, and he called for his bowl, And he called for his fiddlers three. Every fiddler he had a fiddle, And a very fine fiddle had he; Oh there's none so rare, as can compare, With King Cole and his fiddlers three

name: If I Had a Ribbon Bow
comments: First published in 1929 as "Ef I Had a Ribbon Bow" in "Seven Kentucky Mountain Songs as Sung by Marion Kerby and John J, Niles." Niles claimed he collected and arranged this song for this publication. However, Ron Pen, author of "I Wonder as I Wander: The Life of John Jacob Niles" suggests that Niles may have actually written it. In October 1929 Niles performed it at a major chamber music festival held at the Library of  Congress in Washington, D.C. attended by high profile guests including the British ambassador and the wife of the President of the U.S. In 1940 songwriter Lou Singer described it as a folk song which he arranged for singer, Maxine Sullivan. He and Maxine Sullivan had previous success with other folk songs including "Barbara Allen." Singer and his song writing partner, Hughie Prince, copyrighted the song. Consequently, many subsequent recordings of "If I Had a Ribbon Bow" credit them as the writers. Susan Reed, who recorded this song later in the 1940s, described it as an early American folk song found generally throughout the deep South.

name: If My Heart Could Only Talk
Mama Blues
comments: Mostly instrumental song where the instrument (usually a mouth harp/harmonica but can be a banjo or guitar or jazz instrument) "talks" saying "Mama" or "I want my mama". Toward the latter end of the song the musician (or some other person) will ask "What on earth do you want son" and the instrument will say back "I want my mama", then they will continue a related dialog back and forth about calling your mama. William McCoy first recorded this on December 6, 1927, using a mouth harp harmonica.  Presumably McCoy also wrote this but his release didn't indicate authorship. Salty Holmes recorded a harmonica version on December 12, 1947, with the standard dialog between the musician and the instrument that also had no songwriting credits.  In 1950, Holmes released an "answer song" called "I Found My Mama". In 1947, Alvino Rey released a jazz version that was credited to "Salty Holmes". Flatt & Scruggs recorded the most well-known version at their 1963 Carnegie Hall concert and their version ad-libbed more on the dialog and was obiously a banjo version.  Earl Scruggs registered the Work so it's often incorrectly attributed to them.

name: I'm on the Road to Memphis
Lily of the Valley [Jazz]
comments: The Lily of the Valley that New Orleans jazz bands play is the one introduced in 1951 by New Orleans drummer, Paul Barbarin.  He seems to have put it together from sections of What a Friend We Have in Jesus and the theme you can hear very near the end of Red Onion Drag (composed in 1927 by Louis Dumaine and Eddie Jackson and recorded that year by Louis Dumaine's Jazzola Eight). NOTE: There is a Victorian hymn called The Lily of the Valley [I've Found a Friend in Jesus] with words written by William Fry for the Salvation Army. Ira Sankey set it to the music of the song The Little Old Log Cabin in the Lane, which had been composed by Will Hays. So when jazz bands play Lily of the Valley, the composers are often incorrectly given as Fry, Sankey and Hays.

name: Bunch of Violets Blue
comments: Traditional song attributed to multiple authors and popular with Irish singers.  The lyrics can vary but a popular version goes - 1. It was out in a moonlit garden, not far from the ballroom grand. A young lad and his sweetheart went strolling hand in hand. Tomorrow the war would call him; he vowed he would be true. Then from her dress she gave to him a bunch of violets blue. 2. They were only a bunch of violets, a bunch of violets blue, Fresh and fair and fragrant, like diamonds on the dew, Fresh and fair and dainty as he pressed them to his heart. He smiled and said where'er he'd roam, from them he ne'er would part. 3. A soldier boy lay dying upon the cold, cold ground. A bunch of withered violets upon his breast was found. Turning to his comrades, in a feeble voice he sighed: "Take them back and tell her that I wore them till I died." 4. They took the withered violets back, it being on her wedding day. An old man's gold had won her from her soldier far away. An old man's gold had won her from her soldier young and tall, And this was what she said to him that evening at the ball:

name: Lift Him Up, That's All
comments: The verses tell the story of Jesus and the Samaritan woman at the well, found in the Gospel of John at 4:4-30.  The refrain draws from the Gospel of John at 12:32, often interpreted as a prophecy of the Crucifixion and/or the Resurrection of Jesus: And I, if I be lifted up from the earth, will draw all men unto me Oh, lift Him up, that's all, Lift Him up in His word, If you'll tell the name of Jesus everywhere, If you'll keep His name a-ringin' everywhere that you go, He will draw men unto Him. It fell into obscurity until covered by Ralph Stanley in 2002.
